84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DRIVER_MAJOR_REVISION
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLFlex_MAJOR_REVISION {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     String variable to hold the returned version
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SQLFlex_MAJOR_REVISION sVersion
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOGGED_USERS
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the number of native users that are
84023>>>>>>>/// using the driver currently. This number is stored in the variable that
84023>>>>>>>/// is passed with the command.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 MAXIMUM_NUMBER_OF_USERS
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOGGED_USERS {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the number of users
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example LOGGED_USERS sUsers
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        MAXIMUM_NUMBER_OF_USERS
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the maximum number of user allowed by
84023>>>>>>>/// the current license.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOGGED_USERS
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax MAXIMUM_NUMBER_OF_USERS {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the maximum number of users
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// MAXIMUM_NUMBER_OF_USERS sMax
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_DATABASE_NAME
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command overrides the database set in the INT file
84023>>>>>>>/// under DATABASE_SPACE_NAME. Any opens or finds will use the database
84023>>>>>>>/// specified here. This can be used when the database is not stated in
84023>>>>>>>/// the INT file or if the database needs to be dynamically changed for
84023>>>>>>>/// a certain query. If the database is not specified with this command
84023>>>>>>>/// or in the INT file, then the default database for the server will be
84023>>>>>>>/// used. To set the database to be used for embedded SQL statements,
84023>>>>>>>/// use SQL_USE_DATABASE.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, MySQLFlex and PGFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_DATABASE_NAME SQL_USE_DATABASE
84023>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              DATABASE_SPACE_NAME
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_DATABASE_NAME to {database}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// Login "localhost" "user" "pas123" "sql_drv"
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_DATABASE_NAME to "TestDB"
84023>>>>>>>/// Open Customer
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_DATABASE_NAME
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the name of the database
84023>>>>>>>/// currently being used. The name of the database is returned into the
84023>>>>>>>/// specified string. Even though this command works either way, it is
84023>>>>>>>/// typically used when the INT file does not contain the DATABASE_SPACE_NAME.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, MySQLFlex and PgFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See SET_DATABASE_NAME SQL_USE_DATABASE
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_DATABASE_NAME to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the database name
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// GET_DATABASE_NAME to sDbName
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_NAME_SPACE
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name space, or schema, being
84023>>>>>>>/// used with the current application.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PgFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-01 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_NAME_SPACE
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_NAME_SPACE to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned name space.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// GET_NAME_SPACE to sNameSpace
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_NAME_SPACE
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the name space, or schema, to be used
84023>>>>>>>/// for the application. In Postgres, schemas are objects where all the
84023>>>>>>>/// tables,views and indexes are stored. Separate schemas are used to
84023>>>>>>>/// specify relational data. Note that this command will override the
84023>>>>>>>/// NAME_SPACE value in the INT file.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     PgFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-08-14 By Ian Smith
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_NAME_SPACE
84023>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              NAME_SPACE
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_NAME_SPACE to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Name of the name space
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_NAME_SPACE to "public"
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_USE_DATABASE
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify which database is used
84023>>>>>>>/// for SQL statements only. Any normal table queries or changes will
84023>>>>>>>/// still use the default database, this only effects SQL statements.
84023>>>>>>>/// If none is specified then the default database is used. This can
84023>>>>>>>/// be useful if a certain SQL statement needs to query data from a
84023>>>>>>>/// database not currently being used. Note that this only works if
84023>>>>>>>/// the table name is not fully qualified in the SQl statement, i.e.
84023>>>>>>>/// "TestDB.Customer".
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex MySQLFLex PgSQL
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_DATABASE_NAME GET_DATABASE_NAME
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_USE_DATABASE of {server} to {database}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server (Postgre only)
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_USE_DATABASE "testDB"
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW into sID sFirstName sLastName
84023>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84023>>>>>>>///     Showln sFirstName
84023>>>>>>>///     Showln sLastName
84023>>>>>>>/// End
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set the server to be used when
84023>>>>>>>/// opening tables. It will override the SERVER_NAME token in the INT file.
84023>>>>>>>/// If the server is not specified in the INT file or with this command,
84023>>>>>>>/// then the server used during login will be used. This command is only
84023>>>>>>>/// needed when connecting to multiple SQL servers. To set the server to
84023>>>>>>>/// use for embedded SQL statements, use SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER  SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84023>>>>>>>/// @INTOPT              SERVER_NAME
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to {server}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to "localhost"
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//IGS - removed. CURRENT_SERVER is a property of Validation_List_Mixin so this
84023>>>>>>>//               replace conflicts with the property SET message.
84023>>>>>>>//#Replace SET_CURRENT_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name of the server to be used
84023>>>>>>>/// for opening and querying tables.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-07 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_CURRENT_SERVER to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the server name
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER to sServer
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//IGS - removed. CURRENT_SERVER is a property of Validation_List_Mixin so this
84023>>>>>>>//               replace conflicts with the property GET message.
84023>>>>>>>//#Replace GET_CURRENT_SERVER GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify which server to use for
84023>>>>>>>/// embedded SQL statements. By default, the last logged in server will
84023>>>>>>>/// be used. Note that in addition to setting the server, this command
84023>>>>>>>/// also sets the driver to be used. This command is only needed when
84023>>>>>>>/// connecting to multiple servers. To set the server for opening tables,
84023>>>>>>>/// use SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of {constant} to {server}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     MYSQLFLEX, ORAFLEX, PGFLEX, or SQLFLEX
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Name of the server
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of SQLFLEX to "(localdb)\v11.0"
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the server currently being used for
84023>>>>>>>/// embedded SQL statements.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER SET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of {constant} to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     MYSQLFLEX, ORAFLEX, PGFLEX, or SQLFLEX
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the name of the server
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// GET_CURRENT_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION of SQLFLEX to sServer
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOGIN_SQLFLEX
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command allows the user to login with a specified
84023>>>>>>>/// hostname. The default hostname that is passed is the path of the
84023>>>>>>>/// executable. Passing a custom hostname can be very useful for tracking
84023>>>>>>>/// a specific user for different situations. For example, if a company
84023>>>>>>>/// is using a terminal server and a whole sales team logs in under the
84023>>>>>>>/// same username and hostname, locating a specific user could otherwise
84023>>>>>>>/// be difficult. With this command, each user can pass a custom hostname,
84023>>>>>>>/// easily distinguishing themselves from other users.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOGIN_SQLFLEX {server} {username} {password} {hostname}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param server               Server to use for login
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param username     Username to use for login
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param password     Password to use for login
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param hostname     Hostname to use for login
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// LOGIN_SQLFLEX "localhost" "guestUser" "pas123" "WIN-MM7PQS5CP6C"
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to close any open cursors related to
84023>>>>>>>/// an SQL_EXECUTE_STMT. This should be used once the SQL statement has
84023>>>>>>>/// been executed and all rows have been fetched.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-03 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_STMT SQL_EXECUTE_STMT SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW SQL_APPEND_STMT SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT [of {FileName}]
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName             Name of the file (optional)
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_STMT to "SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE STATUS = 'Active' "
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_PREPARE_STMT
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_BINDCOLUMNS_STMT of Customer to DF_BIND_ALL_COLUMNS
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_EXECUTE_STMT of Customer
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW of Customer
84023>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84023>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.FirstName
84023>>>>>>>///     Showln Customer.LastName
84023>>>>>>>/// End
84023>>>>>>>/// SQL_CANCEL_QUERY_STMT of Customer
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description Allows user to turn off the use of index hints on the native
84023>>>>>>>/// server. Setting this command to DEFAULT will cause the server to use the
84023>>>>>>>/// default settings for hints. Hints are off by default in Microsoft SQL
84023>>>>>>>/// Server but are on in Oracle. Care should be taken with changing the
84023>>>>>>>/// default, and should only be used if the diagnostics tool for your server
84023>>>>>>>/// indicates performance problems with the type of queries that are being
84023>>>>>>>/// generated. Note that this can be turned off or on for the whole server
84023>>>>>>>/// or just for a specific table.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// DEFAULT             - The specified server's default settings
84023>>>>>>>/// USE_INDEXHINT       - All Index hints will be used
84023>>>>>>>/// NO_INDEXHINT        - No index hints will be used
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex, ORAFlex
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION of {scopeLevel} {variable} to {constant}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param scopeLevel           TABLE or SERVER. Indicates the scope of the setting
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Either the name of the server or of the table
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     DEFAULT, USE_INDEXHINT, or NO_INDEXHINT
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// NATIVE_OPTIMIZATION of SERVER "localhost" to USE_INDEXHINT
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the locking and row versioning behavior
84023>>>>>>>/// for SQL statements. See the options below for information on the various
84023>>>>>>>/// effects they can have on transactions.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// DEFAULT  - The default isolation level for the server (READ_COMMITTED
84023>>>>>>>/// for MSSQL).
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED - This option is used to prevent dirty reads. A dirty
84023>>>>>>>/// read is when one transaction reads data from another transaction that
84023>>>>>>>/// has yet to be committed. If one transaction fails, the other now is
84023>>>>>>>/// dealing with invalid data. By setting the isolation level to
84023>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED, dirty reads will be avoided by not allowing transactions
84023>>>>>>>/// to deal with any other data that has not been committed yet. However,
84023>>>>>>>/// in between statements within the current transaction, data can be changed
84023>>>>>>>/// by other transactions. This can result in phantom data or non-repeatable
84023>>>>>>>/// reads. Note that this can slow down performance speeds but is usually
84023>>>>>>>/// good practice.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// READ_UNCOMMITTED - This option is the least restrictive isolation level.
84023>>>>>>>/// With this option, dirty reads are allowed, thus no exclusive locks are
84023>>>>>>>/// honored and modified data from one uncommitted transaction can be read
84023>>>>>>>/// by other transactions.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// REPEATABLE_READ - This option is similar to the READ_COMMITTED option
84023>>>>>>>/// in that locks all placed on all transactions and uncommitted data from
84023>>>>>>>///     other transactions cannot be read, preventing dirty reads. However, unlike
84023>>>>>>>/// READ_COMMITTED, new rows that are added by other transactions can be read
84023>>>>>>>/// by the current transaction if it is retried, possibly resulting in phantom
84023>>>>>>>/// reads. This option should not be used unless there is a specific reason to
84023>>>>>>>/// do so.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// SERIALIZABLE - This option is the most restrictive isolation level. With
84023>>>>>>>/// this option, no interaction is allowed between transactions until they
84023>>>>>>>/// have been committed. Similar to READ_COMMITTED, no transaction can deal
84023>>>>>>>/// with any uncommitted data. On top of that though, range locks are placed on
84023>>>>>>>/// all rows being modified until the current transaction is complete. Because
84023>>>>>>>/// concurrency is so low with this option, performance speeds can be much lower
84023>>>>>>>/// and so this should only be used when there is a specific reason to do so.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL of {server} to {constant}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param server                       Name of the server
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param constant                     DEFAULT, READ_COMMITTED, READ_UNCOMMITTED, REPEATABLE_READ, or SERIALIZABLE
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// LOGIN "localhost" "user" "pass123" "SQL_DRV"
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_ISOLATION_LEVEL of "localhost" to READ_COMMITTED
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84023>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_SESSION_PARAMETER
84023>>>>>>>/// @Description There are two sets of code pages used in windows, ANSI and
84023>>>>>>>/// OEM. ANSI is what is commonly used now, but some data still uses the OEM
84023>>>>>>>/// code pages. When migrating data, this command is used to determine whether
84023>>>>>>>/// the OEM data will be translated to ANSI during the migration. For example,
84023>>>>>>>/// migrating passwords with special characters may call for different code
84023>>>>>>>/// pages. Sending true will convert the OEM data to ANSI, sending false will
84023>>>>>>>/// not. Both OEM_TO_ANSI and OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE do essentially the same
84023>>>>>>>/// thing, however since MSSQL has the functionality built in, OEM_TO_ANSI
84023>>>>>>>/// will use MSSQL's built in translation and thus only works with SQLFlex.
84023>>>>>>>/// OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE is internal and built into the driver so it works
84023>>>>>>>/// for all drivers. Note that if using custom entries with
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI then OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE must be used. Also, if
84023>>>>>>>/// there are already custom entries set then turning OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE
84023>>>>>>>/// on will automatically enable those custom translations.
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84023>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84023>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84023>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84023>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_SESSION_PARAMETER {OEM_TO_ANSI/OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE} to {variable}
84023>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Boolean variable enabling or disabling translation
84023>>>>>>>///
84023>>>>>>>/// @Example
84023>>>>>>>/// SET_SESSION_PARAMETER OEM_TO_ANSI to True
84023>>>>>>>
84023>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI Global Integer iChar Integer iOem Integer iAnsi
84025>>>>>>>    Move iChar to MertechInc_sArg1
84026>>>>>>>    move (String(iOem) + "," + String(iAnsi)) to MertechInc_sArg2
84027>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_LICENSE_ENVIRONMENT_SET CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_sArg1 MertechInc_sArg2 CALLDRV_SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84032>>>>>>>    IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84035>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84036>>>>>>>
84036>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84036>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84036>>>>>>>/// @Description In very rare situations, a custom OEM to ANSI translation
84036>>>>>>>/// is needed. When that is the case, this command can be used to create
84036>>>>>>>/// those custom entries. This is done by passing the character numbered
84036>>>>>>>/// position, the OEM value and the ANSI value. Note that
84036>>>>>>>/// OEM_TRANSLATION_STATE must be set to true for these custom entries to
84036>>>>>>>/// work.
84036>>>>>>>///
84036>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84036>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84036>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84036>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84036>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI SET_SESSION_PARAMETER
84036>>>>>>>///
84036>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI {character} to OEM {value1} ANSI {value2}
84036>>>>>>>/// @Param character            Numbered position (0-255) of the character
84036>>>>>>>/// @Param value1                       Character number for the OEM value
84036>>>>>>>/// @Param value2                       Character number for the ANSI value
84036>>>>>>>
84036>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI Global Integer iChar Integer iOem Integer iAnsi
84038>>>>>>>    Move iChar to MertechInc_sArg1
84039>>>>>>>    Move (Repeat(" ", 255)) to MertechInc_sArg2
84040>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_LICENSE_ENVIRONMENT_SET CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_sArg1 MertechInc_sArg2 CALLDRV_GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84045>>>>>>>    IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84048>>>>>>>End_Function
84049>>>>>>>
84049>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84049>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI
84049>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the custom OEM and ANSI values
84049>>>>>>>/// respectively for a given character. If there is no custom translation
84049>>>>>>>/// for the specified character then no error will be raised, but nothing
84049>>>>>>>/// will be returned.
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions There exists a custom translation for the specified character
84049>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84049>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84049>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84049>>>>>>>/// @See
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_CUSTOM_OEM_TO_ANSI {character} to OEM {value1} ANSI {value2}
84049>>>>>>>/// @Param character            Numbered position (0-255) of the character
84049>>>>>>>/// @Param value1                       Variable to hold the OEM value
84049>>>>>>>/// @Param value2                       Variable to hold the ANSI value
84049>>>>>>>
84049>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84049>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING
84049>>>>>>>/// @Description This command toggles off and on the automatic numeric
84049>>>>>>>/// data type remapping built into SQLFlex. When adding or creating
84049>>>>>>>/// smaller numeric columns during a restructure, SQLFlex will change
84049>>>>>>>/// the type to a more specific data type i.e. smallint or tinyint since
84049>>>>>>>/// they are handled more efficiently by the server. Sending false to this
84049>>>>>>>/// command will force SQl to keep the column as a numeric field, preserving
84049>>>>>>>/// the length and precision. Passing true will leave the remapping up to the
84049>>>>>>>/// driver.
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84049>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84049>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84049>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-04 by Aaron Gulack
84049>>>>>>>/// @See
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING to {variable}
84049>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Boolean variable enabling or disabling remapping
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Example
84049>>>>>>>/// Structure_Start hFile
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>///     Create_Field hFile
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>///     SET_AUTOMATIC_NUMERIC_DATATYPE_REMAPPING to False
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_NAME   of hFile iColumn to "Transaction_Count"
84049>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_TYPE   of hFile iColumn to DF_BCD
84049>>>>>>>///     Set_Attribute DF_FIELD_LENGTH of hFile iColumn to 1
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// Structure_End hFile
84049>>>>>>>
84049>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84049>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FORCE_DATE_FORMAT_INIT
84049>>>>>>>/// @Description At times, a stored procedure, function or trigger may
84049>>>>>>>/// alter the default format for dates. This could cause problems because,
84049>>>>>>>/// for example, if a trigger on a table does this, then every time a save
84049>>>>>>>/// takes place on that table, the format for dates will be changed. By
84049>>>>>>>/// sending true to this command, the date formats will reset to their
84049>>>>>>>/// default format. Note that this is essentially the same thing as running
84049>>>>>>>/// the SQL statement: "ALTER SESSION SET NLS_DATE_FORMAT='MM/DD/YYYY'", so
84049>>>>>>>/// in most situations, that should be used instead of this command.
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84049>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84049>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     ORAFlex
84049>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84049>>>>>>>/// @See
84049>>>>>>>///
84049>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FORCE_DATE_FORMAT_INIT to {variable}
84049>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean variable enabling or disabling format reset
84049>>>>>>>
