84114>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ESCAPE_STRING
84114>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to properly escape strings before
84114>>>>>>>/// they are used in embedded SQL statements. This can be extremely
84114>>>>>>>/// important when you do not have full control of the strings being passed
84114>>>>>>>/// to the SQL statement as this will ensure that the strings are properly
84114>>>>>>>/// quoted.
84114>>>>>>>///
84114>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84114>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84114>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84114>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84114>>>>>>>/// @See
84114>>>>>>>///
84114>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_ESCAPE_STRING of {string} to {variable}
84114>>>>>>>/// @Param string               The string to be escaped.
84114>>>>>>>/// @Param variable     Variable to hold the newly escaped string
84114>>>>>>>///
84114>>>>>>>/// @Example
84114>>>>>>>/// SQL_ESCAPE_STRING of "They said to me, 'hello'." to sEscaped
84114>>>>>>>
84114>>>>>>>Function SQLESCAPESTRING Global String sData Returns String
84116>>>>>>>    String sReturnData
84116>>>>>>>
84116>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84118>>>>>>>
84118>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84120>>>>>>>        Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 0 to sReturnData
84121>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_ESCAPE_STRING CALLBACK 0 PASSING sData sReturnData 0 RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84126>>>>>>>    End
84126>>>>>>>>
84126>>>>>>>
84126>>>>>>>    Function_Return sReturnData
84127>>>>>>>End_Function
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        DIRECT_PATH_LOAD
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84128>>>>>>>/// @See
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to initialize all auto increment
84128>>>>>>>/// columns, or sequences in Oracle, of the specified table to be the
84128>>>>>>>/// highest number plus one. This is useful when inserting a large amount
84128>>>>>>>/// of records in the table and the sequence is not being updated because
84128>>>>>>>/// the auto incremented column is being manually filled.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     OraFlex PgFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_INITIALIZE_SEQUENCE of {FileNumber}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The file number
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_APPEND
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to append data to an existing LOB
84128>>>>>>>/// column in the database. When called, the data corresponding field
84128>>>>>>>/// in the buffer is appended to the respective column in the database.
84128>>>>>>>/// This can be very useful when saving data that exceeds VDF size limits
84128>>>>>>>/// but falls within the limits of the SQL database. Note that this command
84128>>>>>>>/// must write to a file that is active and locked. Also the save is handled
84128>>>>>>>/// within the command so no extra calls are needed to save the changes made.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_LOB_ADD_CHUNK
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_APPEND of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being appended to
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
84128>>>>>>>/// Lock
84128>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84128>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Repeat
84128>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84128>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
84128>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84128>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LENGTH
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the length of the data in the
84128>>>>>>>/// specified column. This command must be used after a proper FIND to
84128>>>>>>>/// ensure that a valid record is in the buffer. This can be a useful
84128>>>>>>>/// command for checking if uploaded data exceeds size limits.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LENGTH of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the length
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84128>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_READ
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command reads a chunk of data from a specified LOB
84128>>>>>>>/// column, moving it into its corresponding field buffer. Because the
84128>>>>>>>/// chunk will be moved into the field buffer, it can only be as large as
84128>>>>>>>/// the buffer allows. To account for this, the constants FIRST or NEXT
84128>>>>>>>/// are passed as well indicating whether to grab the first chunk for
84128>>>>>>>/// the buffer or the next. Each chunk grabbed will be as large as allowed.
84128>>>>>>>/// All these things considered, when reading data larger than the field
84128>>>>>>>/// buffer, it is good practice to perform the read in a loop, adding the
84128>>>>>>>/// length each time. Another optional parameter that can be passed is a
84128>>>>>>>/// variable that will store the length of the chunk. Note that a LOB read
84128>>>>>>>/// must be done after a successful find on the record.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_READ of {FileName} {FieldNumber} {FIRST/NEXT} [{length}]
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being read from
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FIRST                        Reads the first chunk of data
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param NEXT                         Reads the next chuck of data (if larger than buffer limit)
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       Variable to hold the chunk length (optional)
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Direct_Output ('binary:Mertech.pdf')
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Index.1
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of customer 13 to liLength
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// While (liLength > 0)
84128>>>>>>>///     Write customer.comments
84128>>>>>>>///     SQL_LOB_READ of customer 13 Next liLength
84128>>>>>>>/// Loop
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Close_Output
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_WRITE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to write data to a LOB column.
84128>>>>>>>/// By passing the file name and field number of the LOB column, this
84128>>>>>>>/// command will take the current value of the respective field in
84128>>>>>>>/// the field buffer, write it to the database and save it. Any data
84128>>>>>>>/// currently in that field will be overridden by the data from the
84128>>>>>>>/// buffer. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
84128>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
84128>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_WRITE of {FileName} {FieldNumber}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the field being written to
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Direct_Input 'C:\Mertech.xml'
84128>>>>>>>/// Lock
84128>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>///    Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84128>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_WRITE of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Repeat
84128>>>>>>>///        Read_Block Customer.Comments 16384
84128>>>>>>>///        SQL_LOB_APPEND of Customer 13 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Until (SeqEOF)
84128>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84128>>>>>>>/// Close_Input
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer By Recnum
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_LOB_LENGTH of Customer 13 to iLength
84128>>>>>>>/// Showln 'Length: ' iLength
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_LOADFROMFILE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command loads an external file into a specified LOB
84128>>>>>>>/// column. After specifying the file name and field number, the path and
84128>>>>>>>/// file must then be passed respectively. When using Oracle, instead of
84128>>>>>>>/// passing the directory, a directory alias must be passed. This alias
84128>>>>>>>/// can be created using a "CREATE DIRECTORY" statement in SQL. For more
84128>>>>>>>/// information on setting this directory alias, see the Oracle help.
84128>>>>>>>/// For other servers, the file must be a local file available to the
84128>>>>>>>/// application that is calling the command. Note that this command must
84128>>>>>>>/// write to a file that is active and locked. Also this command handles
84128>>>>>>>/// the save so no extra calls are needed to save the changes.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_LOADFROMFILE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} From {path} {file}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being used
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param path                         The path of the file, excluding the file name
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param file                         The name of the file, including the extension
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84128>>>>>>>/// Lock
84128>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>///    LOB_TRUNCATE OF customel 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84128>>>>>>>///    // Directory name is case sensitive.
84128>>>>>>>///    // Make sure the name case matches
84128>>>>>>>///    LOB_LOADFROMFILE OF customel 13 FROM "C:\Mertech\FilesToLoad" "Mertech.XML"
84128>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_ERASE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to erase a portion of data from a
84128>>>>>>>/// LOB column. For text fields, the portion of data to be erased is
84128>>>>>>>/// replaced with white space, and in binary fields, with 0X0. To erase
84128>>>>>>>/// a portion of the data, pass the length to erase as well as the number
84128>>>>>>>/// to offset from. For this command to work properly, it must be done
84128>>>>>>>/// after a valid find. Note that the save is handled inside this command
84128>>>>>>>/// so no extra commands are needed to save the changes.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE LOB_TRUNCATE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_ERASE OF {FileName} {FieldNumber} {length} {offset}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file containing the LOB column
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          Number of the LOB column being erased
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param Length                       Length of chunk to erase from column
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param offset                       Starting position for erase
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>/// Lock
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Eq customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>/// LOB_LENGTH OF customer 13 to liTotalLength
84128>>>>>>>/// LOB_ERASE  OF customer 13    liTotalLength 1
84128>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        LOB_TRUNCATE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to trim a LOB column down to a
84128>>>>>>>/// specified length. By passing the table name and column number, the
84128>>>>>>>/// value in the column can then be trimmed down the specified length.
84128>>>>>>>/// This can be a useful command for clearing out a column before entering
84128>>>>>>>/// new data into it. Note that this command must write to a file that is active
84128>>>>>>>/// and locked. Also this command handles the save so no extra calls
84128>>>>>>>/// are needed to save the changes. This command can be used to clear out a field before adding new data
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 LOB_APPEND LOB_LENGTH LOB_WRITE LOB_READ LOB_LOADFROMFILE LOB_ERASE FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax LOB_TRUNCATE of {FileName} {FieldNumber} to {variable}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FieldNumber          The field number
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param length                       New length to truncate to
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Find Gt Customer By Index.1
84128>>>>>>>/// Lock
84128>>>>>>>///    Find Eq Customer by Recnum
84128>>>>>>>///    SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE of Customer 13 to 0 // Customer.Comments
84128>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84128>>>>>>>/// Unlock
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command currently serves no function.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax FLUSH_LOB_BUFFER of {FileName}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param FileName                     Name of the file
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>
