84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to call a stored procedure on the SQL
84128>>>>>>>/// backend. To successfully call a procedure with this command, a string
84128>>>>>>>/// must be passed containing a valid procedure name. In addition, if the
84128>>>>>>>/// procedure takes any arguments, they must also be passed using the constant
84128>>>>>>>/// "passing" along with all of the needed arguments. If the procedure has a
84128>>>>>>>/// return value, then SQL_GET_FUNCTION_RETURN or SQL_FETCH_NEXT_ROW can be
84128>>>>>>>/// used to get the value(s). If an error is found then the indicator "Err"
84128>>>>>>>/// is set to true.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_PROCEDURE
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE {procedure} Passing {argument}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param procedure            Full name of the procedure
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_PROCEDURE "getCustomerStatus" passing sCustomerID sStatus
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_GET_PROCEDURE_PARAMETER 2 to sStatus
84128>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to execute a function stored in MySQL.
84128>>>>>>>/// This is an alternative to building a function with the SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME,
84128>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER and SQL_FUNCTION_EXECUTE commands. This command
84128>>>>>>>/// builds and executes the function by setting the full function name, the
84128>>>>>>>/// parameter(s) to pass and the variable to hold the returned value. Note that
84128>>>>>>>/// this command can only return a single value so SQL_SET_FUNCTION_PARAMETER
84128>>>>>>>/// and SQL_SET_FUNCTION_NAME must be used when dealing with multiple return
84128>>>>>>>/// values.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 CALL_STORED_FUNCTION
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION {function} Returns {variable} Passing {argument}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param function                     Full name of the function
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the returned value
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param argument                     Argument to pass (can be multiple)
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// CALL_MYSQL_STORED_FUNCTION "getCustomerStatus" Returns sStatus passing sCustomerID
84128>>>>>>>/// Showln sStatus
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description Sets the parameters for a MySQL stored function call.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Internal
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     MySQLFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84128>>>>>>>/// @See
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax DO_SET_ALL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS [sParam1 [sParam2 . sParamn]]
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param sParam1.n    Parameters for the stored function
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84128>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
84128>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the number of available MSSQL
84128>>>>>>>/// servers detected in the network. When used with GET_SQLSERVER_NAME,
84128>>>>>>>/// all the available server names can be easily retrieved.
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
84128>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84128>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84128>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84128>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to {variable}
84128>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold number of servers
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// @Example
84128>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
84128>>>>>>>///
84128>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
84128>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
84128>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
84128>>>>>>>///     Increment i
84128>>>>>>>/// Loop
84128>>>>>>>
84128>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVERS Global Returns Integer
84130>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_COUNT RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84135>>>>>>>
84135>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84136>>>>>>>End_Function
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84137>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_SQLSERVER_NAME
84137>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the name of the server based on the
84137>>>>>>>/// specified index number. The number of servers can be retrieved from
84137>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS and the names can be indexed from that
84137>>>>>>>/// number.
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions SQL Server Browser Service is started and firewall is configured properly
84137>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84137>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84137>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84137>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME {index} to {variable}
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param index                The numbered index name to retrieve
84137>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the server name
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// @Example
84137>>>>>>>/// GET_NO_AVAILABLE_SQLSERVERS to iServers
84137>>>>>>>///
84137>>>>>>>/// While (i <= iServers)
84137>>>>>>>///     GET_SQLSERVER_NAME i to sServer
84137>>>>>>>///     Showln sServer
84137>>>>>>>///     Increment i
84137>>>>>>>/// Loop
84137>>>>>>>
84137>>>>>>>Function SQL_AVAILABLE_SQL_SERVER_NAME Global Integer iIndex Returns String
84139>>>>>>>    Local String sName
84139>>>>>>>
84139>>>>>>>    Get MertechInc_Pre_Size_String 80 to sName
84140>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 SQLFLEX Function CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER CALLBACK 0 PASSING sName iIndex CALLDRV_ENUMERATE_SERVER_SERVER RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84145>>>>>>>
84145>>>>>>>    Function_Return sName
84146>>>>>>>End_Function
84147>>>>>>>
84147>>>>>>>
84147>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84147>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
84147>>>>>>>/// @Description Turn on / off Row_Count for specified server.
84147>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84147>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84147>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84147>>>>>>>///
84147>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
84147>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to turn On / Off Row_Count
84147>>>>>>>/// @Param State       TRUE = turn on Row_Count  FALSE = turn off Row_Count
84147>>>>>>>///
84147>>>>>>>/// @Comment This SHOULD ALWAYS BE TURNED ON
84147>>>>>>>
84147>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Integer iState
84149>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84151>>>>>>>
84151>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer iState CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84156>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
84159>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84160>>>>>>>
84160>>>>>>>//IGS - commented out by a.n. Other
84160>>>>>>>//#REPLACE UseRowCountInTransactions SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS
84160>>>>>>>
84160>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84160>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION
84160>>>>>>>/// @Description Gets the Row_Count setting for specified server.
84160>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84160>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84160>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2009-09-21 By Ian Smith
84160>>>>>>>///
84160>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTION OF <Server> To <State>
84160>>>>>>>/// @Param Server      Name of server to get Row_Count state of
84160>>>>>>>/// @Param State       Variable to hold returned value
84160>>>>>>>
84160>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS Global String sServer Returns Integer
84162>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84164>>>>>>>
84164>>>>>>>    Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_ROWCOUNT_IN_TRANSACTIONS CALLBACK 0 PASSING sServer MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84169>>>>>>>
84169>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84170>>>>>>>End_Function
84171>>>>>>>
84171>>>>>>>
84171>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84171>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT
84171>>>>>>>/// @Description This command controls the date format of data returned
84171>>>>>>>/// through embedded SQL. If set to DATAFLEX, then the dates will be
84171>>>>>>>/// returned in whatever format is set in DF_DATE_FORMAT. When set to
84171>>>>>>>/// NATIVE, this command will force dates to return dates in the format
84171>>>>>>>/// specified on the SQL server. Note that in order for the variables to
84171>>>>>>>/// be in the right form, they need to be string variables.
84171>>>>>>>///
84171>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84171>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84171>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84171>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-02 by Aaron Gulack
84171>>>>>>>/// @See
84171>>>>>>>///
84171>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to {DATAFLEX/NATIVE}
84171>>>>>>>///
84171>>>>>>>/// @Example
84171>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_DATE_FORMAT to NATIVE
84171>>>>>>>
84171>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Integer iState
84173>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84175>>>>>>>
84175>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
84177>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84182>>>>>>>        IF MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR TRUE
84185>>>>>>>    End
84185>>>>>>>>
84185>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84186>>>>>>>
84186>>>>>>>Function SQL_USE_DATAFLEX_DATEFORMAT Global Returns Integer
84188>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84190>>>>>>>
84190>>>>>>>    If MertechInc_DriverName eq SQLFlex Begin
84192>>>>>>>        CALL_DRIVER 0 MertechInc_DriverName FUNCTION CALLDRV_USE_DFLEX_DATE_FORMAT CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84197>>>>>>>    End
84197>>>>>>>>
84197>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
84199>>>>>>>
84199>>>>>>>    function_return MertechInc_iRet
84200>>>>>>>End_Function
84201>>>>>>>
84201>>>>>>>
84201>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84201>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84201>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to handle blank
84201>>>>>>>/// and zero values on the SQL backend. Since blank or zero values can
84201>>>>>>>/// often be stored as null in the server database, this command allows
84201>>>>>>>/// that to be altered if needed. When set to true, a value will be
84201>>>>>>>/// inserted into blank records to keep them from being null. See the
84201>>>>>>>/// list below for what value will be stored instead of null. If set to
84201>>>>>>>/// false, values will be stored normally in the database. Note that this
84201>>>>>>>/// command effects all data types.
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
84201>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
84201>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84201>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84201>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84201>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84201>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL GET_FIELDS_NULL
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL to {variable}
84201>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean variable to indicate how to handle null values
84201>>>>>>>///
84201>>>>>>>
84201>>>>>>>Procedure Set SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Integer iState
84203>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84205>>>>>>>
84205>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84207>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING iState MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_SET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84212>>>>>>>        If MertechInc_iRet EQ -1 INDICATE ERR True
84215>>>>>>>    End
84215>>>>>>>>
84215>>>>>>>End_Procedure
84216>>>>>>>
84216>>>>>>>
84216>>>>>>>
84216>>>>>>>
84216>>>>>>>Function SQL_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL Global Returns Integer
84218>>>>>>>    DO_GETFILENUMBER_DRIVERNAME 0
84220>>>>>>>
84220>>>>>>>    If (MertechInc_FileNumber <> -1) Begin
84222>>>>>>>        Call_Driver 0 MertechInc_DriverName Function CALLDRV_FORCE_FIELDS_NOT_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank CALLDRV_VALUE_GET RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84227>>>>>>>    End
84227>>>>>>>>
84227>>>>>>>    Else Move DFFALSE to MertechInc_iRet
84229>>>>>>>
84229>>>>>>>    Function_Return MertechInc_iRet
84230>>>>>>>End_Function
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIELDS_NULL
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to specify how to store blank or zero
84231>>>>>>>/// values in the database. Since database can sometimes store these value,
84231>>>>>>>/// i.e. '' or 0, as null, using this command can be useful in managing that.
84231>>>>>>>/// When set to true, any value in a column of the given type considered blank
84231>>>>>>>/// or 0 will be stored as null in the database. Setting it to false will cause
84231>>>>>>>/// the server to save as it normally would. Note that this command is used to
84231>>>>>>>/// set specific data types only, it can not effect all types at once. Below is
84231>>>>>>>/// a list of value that would be considered blank/zero values.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// DF_ASCII and DF_TEXT -              ' ' (one blank space)
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// DF_BCD -                                    0 (zero)
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// DF_DATe and DF_DATETIME -   00/00/0000 for MYSQL
84231>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/0001 for Oracle MSSQL, and Postgre
84231>>>>>>>///                                                             01/01/1753 for MSSQL Datetimes
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// DF_BINARY -                                 0X0
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Boolean to indicate how to handle blank data
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIELDS_NULL
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command will return the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL for
84231>>>>>>>/// the specified data type.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-08 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIELDS_NULL SET_FIELDS_NOT_NULL
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FIELDS_NULL {datatype} to {variable}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param datatype                     DF_ASCII, DF_BCD, or DF_DATE
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param variable             Variable to hold the value of SET_FIELDS_NULL
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used when scripting structural changes.
84231>>>>>>>/// It is the same as using ENABLE_SCRIPTING and Structure_Start separately.
84231>>>>>>>/// It allows structural changes to be compiled and tested without
84231>>>>>>>/// actually making any of the changes. Any table restructuring done
84231>>>>>>>/// between this command and STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC will not actually be
84231>>>>>>>/// committed but will instead create a mock INT file. The script and
84231>>>>>>>/// INT file can then be retrieved and examined for testing purposes.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        STRUCTURE_END_DYNAMIC
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command ends the scripting started by
84231>>>>>>>/// STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC. It is the same as calling Structure_End
84231>>>>>>>/// and DISABLE_SCRIPTING separately.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Deprecated
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 ENABLE_SCRIPTING DISABLE_SCRIPTING
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax STRUCTURE_START_DYNAMIC of {FileNumber}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param FileNumber                   The number of the file
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description Attachs an MS SQL mdf to the current server instance. If
84231>>>>>>>/// the passed database is already attached, no error is generated.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// The SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB command is intended for use with our new support
84231>>>>>>>/// of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use case might be
84231>>>>>>>/// to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then detach this DB
84231>>>>>>>/// and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using stored procedures,
84231>>>>>>>/// but the code had some complexities that a developer need not worry about.
84231>>>>>>>/// When you attach a database, you must pass the database name, along with
84231>>>>>>>/// the path to an MDF file which contains the database.  Any associated LDF's
84231>>>>>>>/// (log files) and NDF's (secondary data files) must be in the same folder.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// If you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB on a database that is already attached,
84231>>>>>>>/// no error will be generated.  After you call SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB, you
84231>>>>>>>/// should call SET_DATABASE_NAME if you wish to make the attached database
84231>>>>>>>/// the currently selected database.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB will work on all supported version of SQL server.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB {database} on {filePath}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param filePath                     Path of the MDF file
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Example
84231>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_ATTACH_DB "MTSample" ON "C:\Mertech\Data\SampleDb.mdf"
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description The SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB command is intended for use with our
84231>>>>>>>/// new support of Microsoft LocalDB's.  When using LocalDB's a common use
84231>>>>>>>/// case might be to attach to a customer DB, do some work on it, and then
84231>>>>>>>/// detach this DB and attach to a different DB.  This was possible using
84231>>>>>>>/// stored procedures, but the code had some complexities that a developer
84231>>>>>>>/// need not worry about.  A detach can only be done if the database passed
84231>>>>>>>/// has no open connections.  As part of the detach process, the command
84231>>>>>>>/// closes ALL open files (even those not associated with this database or
84231>>>>>>>/// driver).
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// NOTE: SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB will often fail to execute if you are testing
84231>>>>>>>/// your application from the studio.  This is because the studio itself
84231>>>>>>>/// normally has open connections to the database.  If you test your
84231>>>>>>>/// application outside of the studio and the studio is closed (and any
84231>>>>>>>/// other application or tools that access this database are closed) you
84231>>>>>>>/// can successfully detach the database.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     SQLFlex
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB {database}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param database                     Name of the database
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Example
84231>>>>>>>/// SQLSERVER_DETACH_DB "TestDB"
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to a
84231>>>>>>>/// fixed value. This can be useful because doing a SELECT COUNT(*) is
84231>>>>>>>/// a very expensive process to the server. Many applications do counts
84231>>>>>>>/// often and using this command can help cut down the server traffic.
84231>>>>>>>/// Sometimes when counts are used, an exact number is not necessary so
84231>>>>>>>/// a fixed value, updated occasionally can be used. By setting this
84231>>>>>>>/// command to 0 or greater, the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be
84231>>>>>>>/// set to that specified value and the internal SELECT COUNT(*) will be
84231>>>>>>>/// suppressed. If this command is set to something less that zero,
84231>>>>>>>/// DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED will be dynamically calculated whenever it is
84231>>>>>>>/// called.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// The default value for this command is -1
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Fixed value for DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Example
84231>>>>>>>/// SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 10000
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command returns the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>/// if it has been set to a fixed value by SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED.
84231>>>>>>>/// If anything greater than or equal to 0 is returned then that is the
84231>>>>>>>/// fixed value returned by any SELECT COUNT(*) statements, internal or
84231>>>>>>>/// not. If something less than zero is returned, then DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>/// returns a dynamic count whenever it is called.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// By default the value of this is -1
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status              Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax GET_FILE_RECORDS_USED to {variable}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param variable                     Variable to hold the fixed value
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Example
84231>>>>>>>/// GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to iRecords
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command sets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
84231>>>>>>>/// a fixed value of zero. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done,
84231>>>>>>>/// zero is returned, cutting down on server traffic. This is the same
84231>>>>>>>/// as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED to 0.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command resets the value of DF_FILE_RECORDS_USED to
84231>>>>>>>/// -1. That way anytime a SELECT COUNT(*) is done, it returns the actual
84231>>>>>>>/// count of records. This is the same as setting SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>/// to -1.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2013-10-09 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 SUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT SET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED GET_FIXED_FILE_RECORDS_USED
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax UNSUPPRESS_SELECT_COUNT
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>// Private:
84231>>>>>>>// Get the filenumber of a file.field parameter
84231>>>>>>>//
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>// Private:
84231>>>>>>>// Get the fieldnumber of a file.field parameter
84231>>>>>>>//
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//
84231>>>>>>>// Minimum required DataFlex version for new LOB support below is VDF 4
84231>>>>>>>//
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>TYPE tMertechLOB_Args
84231>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize       AS WORD          // always the size of the structure (verification + versioning)
84231>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nField       AS DWORD         // always the field number
84231>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.pszData      AS POINTER
84231>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nSize        AS DWORD
84231>>>>>>>    FIELD tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset      AS POINTER
84231>>>>>>>END_TYPE
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84231>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB
84231>>>>>>>/// @Description This command replaces whatever is currently in a LOB Field
84231>>>>>>>/// with the data passed. It writes to a client side buffer. It can be used
84231>>>>>>>/// to Write an arbitrary amount of data into a LOB.
84231>>>>>>>/// If passed an empty String, it will remove all the contents of the LOB.
84231>>>>>>>/// If you wish to Set a LOB back to NULL, please use the SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84231>>>>>>>/// command.
84231>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_WRITE, this call does not
84231>>>>>>>/// perform the Save. This must be done separately.
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84231>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84231>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84231>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84231>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
84231>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to use to set the field's value
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// @Example
84231>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84231>>>>>>>/// String sLine
84231>>>>>>>///
84231>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84231>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84231>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84231>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84231>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
84231>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84231>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
84231>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
84231>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
84231>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
84231>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
84231>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
84231>>>>>>>///       Loop
84231>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84231>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84231>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
84231>>>>>>>/// End
84231>>>>>>>
84231>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
84234>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args       // can drop local command if minimum vdf version is 6
84234>>>>>>>
84234>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84235>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84235>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84236>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84237>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84238>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84239>>>>>>>
84239>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_WRITE CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84244>>>>>>>End_Procedure // MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB
84245>>>>>>>
84245>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84245>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84245>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to add additional chunks to the buffer
84245>>>>>>>/// before saving the record. After SQL_SET_LOB has been called
84245>>>>>>>/// SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK can be called as many times as needed to add additional
84245>>>>>>>/// chunks of data before a save. It can also be called independent of
84245>>>>>>>/// SQL_SET_LOB to append data to an existing LOB column.
84245>>>>>>>/// NOTE: Unlike the previous call LOB_APPEND, this call does not perform
84245>>>>>>>/// the save. This must be done separately.
84245>>>>>>>///
84245>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84245>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84245>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84245>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84245>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84245>>>>>>>///
84245>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84245>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                The name of the file containing the LOB field
84245>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName               The name of the LOB field being set
84245>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                The variable to add as the LOB chunk
84245>>>>>>>///
84245>>>>>>>/// @Example
84245>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84245>>>>>>>/// String sLine
84245>>>>>>>///
84245>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84245>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84245>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84245>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84245>>>>>>>///    Direct_Input "C:\bigFile.xml"
84245>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84245>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to ""
84245>>>>>>>///       Read_Block sLine 262144
84245>>>>>>>///       SQL_SET_LOB Customer.Comments to sLine
84245>>>>>>>///       While (not(SeqEof))
84245>>>>>>>///          Read_Block sLine 262144
84245>>>>>>>///          SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sLine
84245>>>>>>>///       Loop
84245>>>>>>>///    Saverecord Customer
84245>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84245>>>>>>>///    Close_Input
84245>>>>>>>/// End
84245>>>>>>>
84245>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField String sData
84248>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84248>>>>>>>
84248>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84249>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84249>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84250>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84251>>>>>>>    Put (AddressOf(sData))    to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84252>>>>>>>    Put (length(sData))       to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84253>>>>>>>
84253>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_APPEND CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84258>>>>>>>end_procedure // MertechInc_SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK
84259>>>>>>>
84259>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84259>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB
84259>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting the value of a specified LOB
84259>>>>>>>/// field. Two optional parameters can be passed specifying the offset and
84259>>>>>>>/// length of the chunk to get. Passing these parameters essentially makes this
84259>>>>>>>/// call the same as SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK.
84259>>>>>>>/// Depending on the situation, the two calls can be interchanged for improved
84259>>>>>>>/// code readability. Excluding these additional parameters will get the whole
84259>>>>>>>/// field value within DataFlex variable size limits.
84259>>>>>>>///
84259>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84259>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84259>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84259>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84259>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84259>>>>>>>///
84259>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} [ OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length} ]
84259>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
84259>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
84259>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB value
84259>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB value (optional)
84259>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of value to get from the LOB field (optional)
84259>>>>>>>///
84259>>>>>>>/// @Example
84259>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84259>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84259>>>>>>>///
84259>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
84259>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
84259>>>>>>>///
84259>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84259>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84259>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84259>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84259>>>>>>>///    Direct_Output ('Binary:' + sDestFileName)
84259>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84259>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84259>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84259>>>>>>>///       Write sResult
84259>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84259>>>>>>>///    Loop
84259>>>>>>>///    Close_Output
84259>>>>>>>/// End
84259>>>>>>>
84259>>>>>>>
84259>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Integer iOffset Integer iLength Returns String
84262>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84262>>>>>>>    Local String sData
84262>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
84262>>>>>>>
84262>>>>>>>    Move "" To sData
84263>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84264>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84264>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84265>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84266>>>>>>>
84266>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84271>>>>>>>
84271>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
84272>>>>>>>    If nSize GT 0 Begin
84274>>>>>>>      If (iOffset=0 and iLength=0) Begin
84276>>>>>>>        ZeroString nSize to sData
84277>>>>>>>            //Send Assert (AddressOf(sData) <> 0) ("AddressOf(sData) is NULL") DFTrue
84277>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84278>>>>>>>      End
84278>>>>>>>>
84278>>>>>>>      Else Begin
84279>>>>>>>        ZeroString iLength to sData
84280>>>>>>>        Put (AddressOf(sData)) to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.pszData
84281>>>>>>>        Put iLength            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize
84282>>>>>>>        Put iOffset            to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nOffset
84283>>>>>>>      End
84283>>>>>>>>
84283>>>>>>>      Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_READ CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84288>>>>>>>    End
84288>>>>>>>>
84288>>>>>>>    Else Begin
84289>>>>>>>        Move "" to sData
84290>>>>>>>    End
84290>>>>>>>>
84290>>>>>>>    Function_Return sData
84291>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB
84292>>>>>>>
84292>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84292>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK
84292>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used for getting a chunk of data from a specified
84292>>>>>>>/// LOB field. The difference between this command and SQL_GET_LOB is only that
84292>>>>>>>/// the parameters OFFSET and LENGTH are not optional when using this command.
84292>>>>>>>/// You may consider using this command to retrieve small portions of a very
84292>>>>>>>/// large BLOB so as to reduce memory usage.
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84292>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84292>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84292>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Syntax     SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK {FileName.FieldName} TO {variable} OFFSET {offset} LENGTH {length}
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file that contains the specified LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the LOB chunk
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              offset                          Integer amount to offset when getting the LOB chunk
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              length                          Length of chunk to get from the LOB field
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Example
84292>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84292>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// Move 262144 to iChunkSize
84292>>>>>>>/// Move 0      to iChunk
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84292>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84292>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84292>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84292>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84292>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84292>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84292>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
84292>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84292>>>>>>>///    Loop
84292>>>>>>>/// End
84292>>>>>>>
84292>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84292>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84292>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to get the length of a specified LOB field.
84292>>>>>>>/// It is useful, for example, in determining the number of iterations to
84292>>>>>>>/// perform while reading from a LOB field using chunking.
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84292>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84292>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84292>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH {FileName.FieldName} to {variable}
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
84292>>>>>>>/// @Param              variable                        The variable to hold the length of the field
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// @Example
84292>>>>>>>/// Set_Argument_Size 262144
84292>>>>>>>/// String sResult
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// Move 16384 to iChunkSize
84292>>>>>>>/// Move 0     to iChunk
84292>>>>>>>///
84292>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84292>>>>>>>///    Move iID to Customer.ID
84292>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84292>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84292>>>>>>>///    SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH Customer.Comments to iLength
84292>>>>>>>///    While (iChunk*iChunkSize < iLength)
84292>>>>>>>///       SQL_GET_LOB Customer.Comments to sResult OFFSET (iChunk*iChunkSize) LENGTH iChunkSize
84292>>>>>>>///       // Do something with the LOB data
84292>>>>>>>///       Increment iChunk
84292>>>>>>>///    Loop
84292>>>>>>>/// End
84292>>>>>>>
84292>>>>>>>
84292>>>>>>>Function MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField Returns Integer
84295>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84295>>>>>>>    Local DWord  nSize
84295>>>>>>>
84295>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84296>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84296>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84297>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84298>>>>>>>
84298>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_GET_LENGTH CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84303>>>>>>>
84303>>>>>>>    GetBuff from sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nSize to nSize
84304>>>>>>>    Function_Return nSize
84305>>>>>>>End_Function // MertechInc_SQL_GET_LOB_LENGTH
84306>>>>>>>
84306>>>>>>>//=============================================================================
84306>>>>>>>/// @Name        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84306>>>>>>>/// @Description This command is used to set a LOB column to null. Often
84306>>>>>>>/// LOB columns should either contain data or be null. A "blank" LOB column
84306>>>>>>>/// often doesn't appear empty in other environments, so settings it back to
84306>>>>>>>/// null is best.
84306>>>>>>>///
84306>>>>>>>/// @Assumptions The field being used is a LOB field
84306>>>>>>>/// @Status      Public
84306>>>>>>>/// @Drivers     All
84306>>>>>>>/// @VersionNote Last Revised: 2014-07-10 by Aaron Gulack
84306>>>>>>>/// @See                 SQL_SET_LOB SQL_ADD_LOB_CHUNK SQL_GET_LOB SQL_GET_LOB_CHUNK SQL_LOB_TRUNCATE
84306>>>>>>>///
84306>>>>>>>/// @Syntax             SQL_SET_LOB_NULL    {FileName.FieldName}
84306>>>>>>>/// @Param              FileName                        The name of the file containing the LOB field
84306>>>>>>>/// @Param              FieldName                       The name of the specified LOB field
84306>>>>>>>///
84306>>>>>>>/// @Example
84306>>>>>>>////
84306>>>>>>>/// Clear Customer
84306>>>>>>>/// Move iID to Customer.ID
84306>>>>>>>/// Find Eq Customer by Index.1
84306>>>>>>>/// If (Found) Begin
84306>>>>>>>///    Reread Customer
84306>>>>>>>///        SQL_SET_LOB_NULL Customer.Comments
84306>>>>>>>///        Saverecord Customer
84306>>>>>>>///    Unlock
84306>>>>>>>/// End
84306>>>>>>>
84306>>>>>>>
84306>>>>>>>Procedure MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB_NULL String sDriver Integer iFile Integer iField
84309>>>>>>>    Local String sLOB_Args
84309>>>>>>>
84309>>>>>>>    ZeroType tMertechLOB_Args to sLOB_Args
84310>>>>>>>    // First move the size of the structure to the Structure
84310>>>>>>>    Put tMertechLOB_Args_size to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.cbSize
84311>>>>>>>    Put iField                to sLOB_Args at tMertechLOB_Args.nField
84312>>>>>>>
84312>>>>>>>    Call_Driver iFile sDriver Function CALLDRV_LOB_EX_SET_NULL CALLBACK 0 PASSING MertechInc_Blank MertechInc_Blank (addressof(sLOB_Args)) RESULT MertechInc_iRet
84317>>>>>>>End_Procedure // MertechInc_SQL_SET_LOB_NULL
84318>>>>>>>
84318>>>>>>>
84318>>>>>>>
